## Key Design Decisions

### Co-located Source

Catalog pages live alongside the component's API definitions at `apis/dev/planton/provider/{provider}/{component}/v1/catalog-page.md`. This keeps documentation close to the code it describes and makes it natural for component forge workflows to create the catalog page as part of the component creation process.

### Gradual Migration

The build script checks for `catalog-page.md` first, falls back to `docs/README.md` (the legacy research document). This allows components to be migrated one at a time from research docs to proper catalog pages without breaking the site.

### Title Extraction from H1

Rather than requiring frontmatter in source files (which the build script adds during copy), titles are extracted from the first `# ` heading in the content. This keeps source files clean and lets human authors write naturally. The H1 includes the provider prefix (e.g., `# Hetzner Cloud Certificate`) for context when reading the source file directly.

### Provider Prefix Stripping

The `PROVIDER_PREFIXES` map strips provider names from H1 headings to produce sidebar labels. This way, the sidebar shows just "Certificate" under "HETZNER CLOUD" instead of redundantly showing "Hetzner Cloud Certificate". The H1 heading in the rendered page still includes the full name for standalone readability.

### Slug Generation

Titles are converted to URL-friendly slugs: lowercase, spaces to hyphens, special characters removed. This produces clean URLs like `/docs/catalog/aws/route53-dns-record` instead of `/docs/catalog/aws/awsroute53dnsrecord`.

### Internal Link Rewriting

Source catalog pages use stable directory-name-based links (e.g., `/docs/catalog/aws/awsvpc`) because directory names don't change when titles are adjusted. The build script rewrites these to slug-based URLs at build time using a global lookup table.

### Provider Display Names

Provider titles in the sidebar and catalog grid come from the `PROVIDER_DISPLAY_NAMES` map (uppercased version of the proto `display_name`), not from raw directory name uppercasing. This handles multi-word names correctly (e.g., "HETZNER CLOUD" vs "HETZNERCLOUD").

